proportions of national healthcare budgets. The relatively young field of 
longevity research, after accumulating insights into the mechanisms of aging and 
producing dramatic laboratory demonstrations of life extension in some 
organisms, is entering the translational phase. This phase, through clinical 
trials, will confirm or refute the "geroscience hypothesis" that drugs can 
change the trajectory of the processes of aging within cells, and ultimately in 
living humans. At the same time, traditional funding patterns do not favor such 
visionary "moonshot" research, which, despite the potential for ultimately 
providing benefits for everyone, offers little prospect for rapid return on 
investment and high probabilities for early phase failure. New radical funding 
strategies incentivizing innovation will have to be called into play.

