and C (67.5%), respectively. Overall, 168 DRMs were found in 63 (73.3%) samples, 
and 105 (62.5%) of them were minority variants. Among DRMs, 41 (39.0%) minority 
variants and 33 (52.4%) variants with frequency above 20.0% in the viral 
population were able to confer some degree of resistance to at least one drug in 
use by respective patients, yet no one showed signs of therapeutic failure.
CONCLUSIONS: Our study contributes to the understanding of the impact of DRMs on 
successful therapy and supports the sustainability of combinatorial ART, because 
all patients maintained their successful treatment despite the high prevalence 
of DRMs at low (62.5%) or high (37.5%) frequency.

